<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do you calculate an anniversary?", answer: "Pick the date of the event you want to celebrate (first date, wedding date, day you met) and count forward. The 1-year anniversary is the same calendar date one year later. The 2-year is two years later, and so on. The calculator handles leap years automatically — if your anniversary falls on Feb 29, it shows up correctly in non-leap years (most couples celebrate on Feb 28 or March 1)." },
  { question: "What are the traditional anniversary gifts by year?", answer: "Year 1 is paper, year 2 is cotton, year 3 is leather, year 5 is wood, year 10 is tin or aluminum, year 15 is crystal, year 20 is china, year 25 is silver, year 30 is pearl, year 40 is ruby, year 50 is gold, year 60 is diamond. The 'modern' US list (created by jewelers in the 1940s) replaces some traditional gifts with more luxurious options — for example, modern year 5 is silverware, modern year 10 is diamond jewelry." },
  { question: "Should we celebrate dating anniversaries or only the wedding anniversary?", answer: "It's entirely personal. Many couples celebrate both — the anniversary of their first date or the day they became official, plus the wedding anniversary. Others drop the dating anniversary once married. Still others celebrate the day they met. The 'right' anniversary to celebrate is the one that matters most to you, and the calculator works with whichever date you pick." },
  { question: "What's the most important anniversary?", answer: "The 1st (newlywed milestone), 5th (first major anniversary, often celebrated with a trip), 10th (decade), 25th (silver, often a renewal of vows), and 50th (gold, the gold standard of marriage longevity). Each gets disproportionate cultural attention. Some research suggests the 7-year anniversary is also important — 'the seven year itch' is a real phenomenon, with divorce rates spiking around years 5–8 of marriage." },
  { question: "How do you celebrate an anniversary?", answer: "Anything that feels meaningful and intentional. Common options: dinner at the restaurant of your first date, a trip back to your honeymoon location, exchanging gifts that match the traditional list (paper for year 1, leather for year 3), writing letters to each other, doing the same thing you did on your first date, or simply spending the day together with no plans. The 'how' matters less than the 'we made time for this'." }
]) %>

