    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How the Anniversary Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        Pick the date your relationship started — your wedding day, the day you met, your first date, whichever moment you celebrate. The calculator counts forward to today using exact calendar arithmetic, breaking the result into years, months, and days. It also counts the total number of days (great for milestone celebrations like 1,000 or 5,000 days), figures out when your next anniversary falls, and suggests the traditional gift for that year. Leap years are handled correctly — Feb 29 anniversaries display properly in non-leap years.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Traditional Anniversary Gifts by Year</h2>
      <p>
        The traditional anniversary gift list dates back to medieval Europe and was formalized by US jewelers in the 1930s and 1940s. Year 1 is paper, year 2 is cotton, year 3 is leather, year 4 is fruit or flowers, year 5 is wood, year 10 is tin or aluminum, year 15 is crystal, year 20 is china, year 25 is silver, year 30 is pearl, year 35 is coral, year 40 is ruby, year 45 is sapphire, year 50 is gold, year 55 is emerald, year 60 is diamond, and year 75 is diamond and gold. Modern lists (created by jewelers to sell more jewelry) replace the cheaper materials with more luxurious ones.
      </p>

      <h2>Why People Track Anniversaries</h2>
      <p>
        Anniversaries are markers — they punctuate the unspoken stretches of relationship time and force you to look back, reflect, and reconnect. Couples who actively celebrate anniversaries (even simple ones, like a card and dinner) report higher relationship satisfaction in research from the Gottman Institute and the National Marriage Project. The ritual of marking the date matters more than the gift or the spend. Couples who let anniversaries slide year after year tend to drift, while couples who plan something — even small — tend to stay connected.
      </p>

      <h2>Beyond Years: Tracking Total Days</h2>
      <p>
        Some couples like tracking total days for fun milestones — 100 days, 500 days, 1,000 days, 5,000 days. The calculator gives you the total day count, which makes it easy to plan a "1,000 days together" celebration or post a sentimental anniversary on social media. The day count also makes long relationships feel real — 10 years sounds abstract, but 3,652 days sounds like a lot of mornings, dinners, and conversations.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Which date should I use for an anniversary?</h3>
      <p>The one that matters most to you. Wedding date, first date, day you met — there's no wrong answer.</p>

      <h3>Are anniversaries really important for relationships?</h3>
      <p>Research says yes — couples who mark anniversaries report higher satisfaction than couples who don't.</p>

      <h3>What should I get for a 5-year anniversary?</h3>
      <p>Traditional is wood, modern is silverware. A weekend getaway is also popular for the 5-year mark.</p>

      <h3>How do same-sex couples handle traditional gift lists?</h3>
      <p>The lists are gender-neutral — just pick gifts that fit your style, ignore the ones that don't.</p>

      <h3>What's the longest anniversary celebration?</h3>
      <p>Various sources put it at 90+ years — anniversaries beyond 75 are extremely rare due to lifespan.</p>

      <%= render "shared/print_button" %>
      <%= render "shared/calculation_email_capture" %>
    </article>

